The third edition of the under 19 South- Cricket tournament tagged Jide Bademosi Cup is presently taking place in Oyo State capital, Ibadan. The tournament which started on Wednesday and will be concluded on Sunday with teams from Lagos, Ogun, Osun, Ondo, Ekiti and the host Oyo States battling for honour at the Obafemi Awolowo Cricket Pitch, Ibadan, Oyo State The Tournament Director, Okon Ukpong said the event was organized to awakening the South West region. Ukpong , a former Nigeria and West Africa cricket captain, further said the under 19 tournament was another way to prepare South West for a stronger presence at the regional elites level. He said: “Professor Jide Bademosi is our Icon and we need to celebrate him, the six states in the South-West have confirmed their participation for the 3rd edition of the Bademosi Cup.   Klitschko brothers ‘ready to die’ fighting for Ukraine     Cricket revival in Kaduna excites Onoja     GCI Trumps GCI to firm up Second Place at the CCC League   “The South West under-19 event is basically a reawakening to the region especially based on the development of the game in the other regions in the country which we don’t want to lag behind. “We made up our minds to see interms of players potentials and that is why we did not organize Under-17 championship because there is a region that organized National Under-17 cricket developmental programme but we resulted in putting Under-19 tournament on ground. “Organizing the Under 19 competition is to prepare South West for stronger regional presence for the elites level and we all know that Professor Bademosi made a tremendous contribution to the development of cricket in South-West especially in Oyo State which is why the competition was named after him to appreciate his relentless effort on development of cricket over the years.” The former Chairman of the Oyo State Cricket Association and Chairman Technical Committee of the Nigeria Cricket Federation, NCF, praised the present board of the NCF headed by Uyi Akpata for their immense effort in doing the right thing, adding what the South West was doing is complementary. He further advised the board to look at critically at the capacity content of coaching which would make the country more visible internationally.